EAI Practicum 2.2

Classification Problems I.

In the following exercise we’ll use the FIFA data set containing information on 19 239 players enrolled in the season of 22, including columns related to: player’s role, player_positions, preferred_foot and skills.

Modelling Aims

Our goal is to discriminate offensive from all other players based on information we have on them, such as skill characteristics, foot preference, etc. That means we will create an ordinary logistic regression model to perform a binary classification of football players.

The process of fitting a logistic regression model will require from you to:

  • understand your data,

  • chose the right modeling function (logistic, poisson, etc.),

  • capture and process the information from an object created by the modelling function,

  • understand what logistic model delivers and how decision rules work on modelled probabilities,

  • evaluate error of a model fit, and when needed, refine the model,

  • validate your findings on fresh data.

Data Exploration

In the previous exercise, we have shown that if you are an offensive player, pretty much every skill positively correlates with your overall value (Y axis). Let’s revisit these data once again. This time, we will plot skill_dribbling on X axis and color-code four player positions.

The figure shows that overall score correlates well with skill_dribbling — which is one of the most difficult ball skills to master and one of the most useful attacking moves. For every player role on the pitch, the higher the dribbling skill is, the higher his overall score will be.

However, the distribution of skill points is role-dependent. You will rightly assume that top strikers, wingers and forwarders will have dribbling skills almost maxed out. Goal keepers, not so much.  

The box also plot hint us that we can use skill_dribbling attribute to separate offensive players and goal keepers almost perfectly. For every other player role, you have to make compromises.

Hypothesis Formulation

Technically speaking, the word “hypothesis” is a Greek word that means “an assumption subject to verification”.

Here, we will use the logistic function to predict the player’s role by regressing onto his dribbling skills and information about preferred foot. We assume that there might be a relationship between higher skill_dribbling values and the chance of a footballer playing in offense.

To make things clean, we will formulate two hypotheses:.

  • H0: Higher dribbling skill value is not enough to classify a player as an offensive player (vs. player playing any other position).

  • H0: Playing with left foot has no impact on the player’s role.

Remember that the null hypothesis is always stated in the negative. This is because we will build a logistic regression model to prove one, both or none of the H0 hypotheses are true.

Model Fitting

In logistic regression,

  • we work with a binary outcome, such as “yes/no,”.

  • The goal is to predict the probability of the positive outcome (e.g., “being offensive player”) based on the predictor variables.

The hypotheses will hold true, if we can separate offensive players from the rest based on skill_dribbling values and/or playing foot preference. If no clear distinction can be made, then it will be imperative to set a line that can minimizes the miss-classification rate of both classes.

Logistic regression is implemented by the glm() function with the following syntax:

glm(formula, data, family = binomial)

where formula is symbolic. The family parameter stipulates the exact form of the glm() function.

The Logistic Function

The logistic function refers to the S-shaped curve that models the probability of a player’s class, thus ranging between 0 and 1. 0 means that there is no chance of a player ever playing in attack, and 1 means that the player will always play in offense.

Task 5: Visualize how the logistic function fits onto our data by completing the following code. Without knowing much about the grammar of graphics functions, fill in only variables needed for X and Y axis to be specified.

data %>%
  ggplot(., aes(...)) + # Define variables for X an Y axix in aes()
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 0.3, height = 0.06), 
             alpha = 0.05, 
             shape = 1, 
             size = 1.5) + 
  stat_smooth(method = glm, method.args = list(family = binomial)) +
  ggtitle("Dribbling Skill Across Player Roles", 
          subtitle = "Offensive players: top, Other players: bottom")

The logistic function flips to the other side when the skill_dribbling attribute is about 60-ish (which equals to the probability of ~ 0.5). It is not a perfect flip, suggesting that we have to deal with a lot of miss-classified observations.

Probabilities and Probability Cut-Offs

The coefficients of the logistic regression are not really useful in practice, so we will work with model probabilities instead. The key thing at this stage is to convert them into discrete binary outcomes — player classes, that is. You can do it by setting up a decision rule that classifies

  • a player to play in offense if his probability is >= 0.5,
  • and a player to play in defense if his probability is < 0.5.

The conversion process can be hard to imagine, so let’s describe the relationship between data, player classes, probabilities and probability cut-offs on the following figure.

To turn probabilities into player classes, you need to:

  • fit a logistic function onto the data.

  • The function shape will be used to estimate class 1/“yes” probabilities for every player. Class 1 is determined by one-hot encoding during data transformation phase. In your case, it is offense.

  • Apply the cut-off to probabilities. If their probability is less that 0.5, the player will be classified as a defensive player. Otherwise, the player will be classified as an offensive player.
